nging together scholars in archaeology, economics, ethnohistory, geography, history, and anthropology. The papers in this volume reflect recent developments in several specific areas of research: mapping, native cultures, social and labour history, personalities, the Pacific coast, and economics. The moving of the Hudson's Bay Archives from London to Winnipeg in 1974 has patriated an incredibly rich source of information on many aspects of Canadian history, and the effects of this superb collection being available to Canadian scholars are just beginning to be felt. In this volume we can see that the history of the fur trade in Canada is not merely the story of the world's first great multi-national – the Hudson's Bay Company – but a study of a complex society during a period of more than two centuries. Languages, customs, transportation, personalities, marriage, and even sex are looked at in the wide-ranging papers in this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFur tradezNorth AmericaxHistoryvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBishop, Charles A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Jennifer S.H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullen, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaenen, Cornelius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Stephen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJudd, Carol M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJudd, Carol, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLewis, G. Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Calvin, 